      h3.title User Freedom <br>
      p.projwords The user’s intellectual and tangible faculty of action—their agency—is extended by the use of computer programs. This is a ‘demand-side’ concern. When a society is premised upon consent, every user retains freedom of agency to run software for any purpose, to not run it, to study how the program works, to adapt it to specific needs, to copy the program and to redistribute copies, to improve the program, and to release any modified versions.
